name: Anonymous
com:
/vst/ is a place to discuss all types of strategy video games, including both turn-based and real-time strategy, turn-based and real-time tactics, single-player and multi-player (including MOBAs). All platforms are welcome.

Does this mean discussion of strategy games is banned on other video game boards? No! /vst/ is just a separate board specifically focused on strategy games where discussions about your favorite games can thrive.

Please familiarize yourself with the rules and remember to use the spoiler function where appropriate!

Please note that, like /v/, "Generals"—long-term, one-after-the-other, recurring threads about a specific game are not permitted on /vst/. Such threads belong on >>>/vg/

The layout of your city changes depending on what services are provided, so you can have low-density, high-wealth suburbs with fully funded schools and hospitals and parks, and low-wealth high-density slums with none of that and no roads next to heavy industry. It isn't linear level-up, and in fact low-wealth is often more useful.

But at the same time Simcity 4 is a grid game. I tried to recreate Sapporo because it's the one city in Japan that was built as a modern planned city and there are good maps of the city layout. This worked to a point. The problem is that the city center may be a grid, but the outlying districts shift the grid 45 degrees, and SC4 is just not designed to handle that. You can't even build diagonal streets in the unmodded game, though you can build roads. Buildings don't grow in at angles, either, not unless you download ones that do. You can't build diagonal bridges either. It really isn't designed for cities that aren't laid out at perfect right angles. If I were playing CS or another game with spline roads I wouldn't have this problem.', 'filename': 'maps', 'ext': '.png', 'w': 1596, 'h': 919, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 71, 'tim': 1670757691722387, 'time': 1670757691, 'md5': '/tnkO7ZDl/IHjDz+oRlIxA==', 'fsize': 1766456, 'resto': 1229303}]

Doesn't cav traditionally chase down and run archers off?', 'time': 1670346428, 'resto': 1108781}, {'no': 1278386, 'now': '12/07/22(Wed)09:25:08', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1277460
Just because cavalry can effectively destroy missile units doesn't mean they are immune to missile damage. Cavalry with barely any missile defense will get crushed javelins, fire arrows and even slings.

>Doesn't cav traditionally chase down and run archers off?

Yes but like all units, some cavalry are more specialized than others. In general, light melee cavalry will be the best to hunt light and fleeing units because of their speed for hit and run. While heavier melee/shock cavalry are made to flank and break down enemy troops. Missile cavalry are meant to pepper/bait enemy units but are weak in melee.

Then you have things like Spet Xyon Archers who could tank missile projectile for days, be decently durable in melee as a missile cavalry and still dish lots of damage in return both in melee and missile.', 'time': 1670423108, 'resto': 1108781}, {'no': 1281420, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)18:40:34', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1277427

com: I know it had a rocky launch and myriad overpriced DLC packs, but in terms of actual gameplay, Rome II is still one of my favourite Total War titles. Anybody have any mod recommendations for this absolute kino? I've heard DEI is good but it sounds a bit slow for my liking.
last_replies:
[{'no': 1281239, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)14:10:22', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1281207
Interesting. I'm the complete opposite. I hate the default Rome II unit cards. Everything looks way too similar and the Greek pottery look is just ugly to me. I really like DEI's unit cards, they remind me of the illustrations in those Osprey Publishing history books I read as a kid.', 'filename': 'osprey', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 900, 'h': 1213, 'tn_w': 92, 'tn_h': 125, 'tim': 1670699422250971, 'time': 1670699422, 'md5': '7gGkCVrtkiF7Ch/HLojRSA==', 'fsize': 288500, 'resto': 1262056}, {'no': 1281259, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)14:35:26', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1281040
>the whole limiting of buildings thing
This comes from Empire. I think that Rome 2 finally gets it right though, the problem with Shogun 1 to Medieval 2 was that you'd have too many buildings to build to fully upgrade a province, it was especailly annoying in Shogun and Medieval 1 because it'd take 4 turns to build a fort just to then spend 2 more turns building a unit building that could only recruit absolute garbage units and 12 turns to build a keep with another 2-4 turns to build a decent unit building, it made expansion take forever. In Rome 1 and Medieval 2 if you didn't abuse the population mechanic it could take even longer. Rome 2 lets you build your unit buildings completely separate from the city upgrades, which speeds up conquest considerably. The issue with Empire to Shogun 2 though, was that you didn't have that many buildings to build, so it was too simplistic. Rome 2 finally gives us a ton of buildings, while making sure not to slow conquest down to such a degree that the campaign becomes boring
>the food supply
This comes from Shogun 2. Unfortunately they didn't update this mechanic. It would have been nice if you could get food from trade, since that's how the Romans got food. It would have also been cool if historical bread baskets like Egypt would produce extra food. Though there are also unique buildings that can produce food and an edict as well. This mechanic is designed to prevent you from building tall and wide too early. But you can build 3 farm buildings in a single small town, so it's not too much of a hindrance
>the dumb secessions
These only happen when you fail to keep the other political parties happy. If you really dislike this mechanic then play a minor faction like Sparta who only has 1 other party. Rome is probably the worst with this since they get 3 extra parties, but that's part of the fun of playing Rome. The political system has a lot of ins and outs
Part 1/2', 'time': 1670700926, 'resto': 1262056}, {'no': 1281264, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)14:43:35', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1281259
part 2/2
Avoiding the civil wars is easy enough. First read what the party likes/dislikes. They have 2 inherent to the party and 1 extra that comes from the party leader. Make sure to do the positives and avoid the negatives, so you keep a really high loyalty. Next make sure to assign at least one of them as a general, this general is gonna need to win a lot. The more they win, the more loyal their party becomes, losses decrease this though. Next be sure to occasionally use political actions to favor that party, such as promoting one of their members. You can also use the map feature (the compose under the minimap), to see what political parties own which provinces. Parties can only own whole provinces (unless you only control part of one, in which case they own all that you own there). Fully conquer one of these provinces and use an edict that gives them loyalty
Of course this mostly works for just 1 party, if you have multiple parties it requires juggling each one. Usually the more powerful factions are balanced by having to manage more parties', 'time': 1670701415, 'resto': 1262056}, {'no': 1281279, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)14:55:20', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1281239
Oh, I mean, I don't hate the style, it's just that it looks badly done or old', 'time': 1670702120, 'resto': 1262056}, {'no': 1281378, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)17:40:06', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1281207

I dropped it after an hour because it seemed like the combat would be extremly basic and repetitive (I suppose it's all just dealing with Action Points while using various weapons with only either range, damage or AP cost changing and maybe some simple mechanics like Healing, Lockpicking, basic AoE explosives, no? BG came out a year before this game)', 'time': 1670351620, 'resto': 1242082}, {'no': 1277638, 'now': '12/06/22(Tue)15:05:12', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1277517
it's an armed conflict so yes, primarily combat will be shooting guns
but there's a bit more than just that, if you can be bothered with it

if you have a strong and athletic sim, you can take chances on running up to enemies and knocking them out with hand-to-hand combat
if you knock out an enemy, you can steal the weapon he's holding (enemies don't always drop the weapon after dying but you can always try to steal it off them as long as they have it equipped)

when a fight in a sector starts but before the enemy actually spots you (not equivalent with turn-based mode being used), you will be in a stealthier "low awareness" mode. enemies will have a slightly less effective field of view, will generally walk or stand around rather than run, and are easier to get one-hit stealth kills on (especially with throwing knives)
some sectors are more rewarding to complete by doing them stealthily, for example in one of the sectors in Alma, you can get a special weapon if the alarm isn't raised

also, if you slip away from a sector without alerting or otherwise being spotted by the enemy, it doesn't count as a battle, so you won't lose team morale for doing so. you can use this for example to try slipping through town sectors without engaging enemies', 'time': 1670357112, 'resto': 1242082}, {'no': 1280929, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)06:44:37', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1242082

com:
is a grand STRATEGY GAME that I have been developing, it's not "off-topic", even if it isn't complete.
Set in pseudo-Europe and inspired by Imperator, it seeks not to be another map painter but an empire manager, with a focus on:
>resource management (you need wood to build ships, grain to feed pops, wool to prevent them from freezing, etc)
>pop management (who all have their wealth)
>character management
>closed economy with prepaid-model
>anti-omniscience (limited information, e.g. you don't know many troops other countries have)
>faction management (all characters belong to a faction, and everything you do impact the faction's loyalty, if you go to war against the faction's beloved country, they might revolt against you)
>army management (army depletes as you advance because you have to leave troops behind to garrison)
>making the world evolve (you turn forests into farmlands, build bridges over rivers, convert villages to cities)

No
The roi for making something so well designed and complex enough to provide a realistic simulation is just not worth it for developers.

Those who would find realistic simulations appealing are usually too busy better things with their spare time than spending it on a game. So the potential market for such a game declines exponentially the more realistic it becomes.

Its just not the game design aspect. There are also two other attributes that throw a spanner in the works. Firstly you also have to design an online compatibility so players can easily engage against each other, Because AI just does not cut it for anyone with an IQ above normal. Then secondly that online PvP mode has to have a system that mitigates griefing, rage quitting, and poor connection. No smart and mature guy wants to waste his time playing against someone playing on a potato, or a 12 year old no-nothing fuckwit, or a trolling high school failure. No developer has ever addressed these issues becasue at the end of the day its just not profitable enough. As allies, you have access to snipers and mortars from the get-go, and your infantry, in general, is superior in terms of health and firepower and doesn't suffer from mp drain as badly as axis units, with the exception of UKF. The UC can kite endlessly with proper micro to stay out of range of fausts and, if upgraded with an mg or flamethrower, will require an ambush from shreks or be forced back by an AT gun. AP ammo isn't available until vet 1, so unless you are face charging into mgs it shouldn't even be an issue, and using it means axis has fewer munitions for snares or weapon upgrades which are the only things keeping grens viable when compared to allied inf. Unless the wher player is opting to start with double mgs and pioneers, you should at most be facing 1 pioneer, 1 gren, and a mg 42 team at the start of the round. All of them are fairly fragile if caught out of position and will likely arrive after you if you rush fuel.
